        <h3>Understanding Prostate Cancer</h3>
        <p>
          Prostate cancer occurs when abnormal cells grow uncontrollably in the prostate gland.
          It is one of the most common cancers among men, especially those over 50.
        </p>
        <p>
          Early detection significantly improves treatment success and survival rates.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="article-section">
        <h3>Common Signs & Symptoms</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Frequent urination, especially at night</li>
          <li>Difficulty starting or stopping urination</li>
          <li>Weak or interrupted urine flow</li>
          <li>Blood in urine or semen</li>
          <li>Pain in the lower back, hips, or pelvis</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="article-section">
        <h3>Risk Factors</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Age (risk increases after 50)</li>
          <li>Family history of prostate cancer</li>
          <li>Diet high in red meat and low in fruits/vegetables</li>
          <li>Obesity and sedentary lifestyle</li>
          <li>African descent (higher prevalence in men of African origin)</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="article-section">
        <h3>Myths vs Facts</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Myth:</strong> Prostate cancer only affects older men</li>
          <li><strong>Fact:</strong> Risk increases with age, but younger men can be affected</li>
          <li><strong>Myth:</strong> Prostate cancer always shows symptoms early</li>
          <li><strong>Fact:</strong> Early stages may be symptomless, so regular screening is important</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

